Regularization Teachniques¶

Imports¶

Please note: for this tutorial we are using the HCAIM Data sets for teaching ethical AI, the Census Dataset.

This was adapted from: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.datasets.load_boston.html

Please note that this dataset is being used as it is a common dataset with ethical concerns. One example is the class bias. None of these have been adderssed for this tutorial.

The aim of this tutorial is to get an understanding of the effects of Regularization Teachniques.

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from numpy import*
from sklearn import*


# sklearn 10FCV
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_predict
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split


# Keras
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow import keras
import numpy as np
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.layers import GaussianNoise
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping

from tensorflow.keras.wrappers.scikit_learn import KerasClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

seed = 1
# fix random seed for reproducibility
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed)


filename = "adult.csv"
data = pd.read_csv(filename)

plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (12,8)

Step 1 - Data pre-processing¶

Some of the columns are currently categorical. They also contain unknow values where some are identified by "?". For this tutorial, the data is pre-processed:

  • The dataset is labelled encoded (including missing data as the same value, for example "?")
  • The dataset is normalised

While additional pre-process and investigations could have been (and should be) conducted, for this tutorial on hyperparameter tuning which focuses on the effects of specific changes for each hyperparameter, this addiotnal pre-processing was not conducted, but can and should be for the lab.

In [2]:
# Used to label encode categorical values

labelencoder = LabelEncoder()

print("\n\nColumn Names & formatting:\n")


for col in data.columns.values.tolist():
    if data[col].dtype == "object" or data[col].dtype == "bool":
        print("{:<30}".format(col), ":", "{:<30}".format(str(data[col].dtype)) , "Formatting to LabelEncoding")
        data[col] = labelencoder.fit_transform(data[col])
    else:
        print("{:<30}".format(col), ":", "{:<30}".format(str(data[col].dtype)) , "No formatting required.")


# Normalizing the input values (excluding the class value)

# Convert to array
array = data.values

# get seperated input and classifies, using a deep copy of a list
X = array[:,0:14]
Y = array[:,14]

scaler = preprocessing.Normalizer().fit(X)
normalizedX = scaler.transform(X)


Column Names & formatting:

age                            : int64                          No formatting required.
workclass                      : object                         Formatting to LabelEncoding
fnlwgt                         : int64                          No formatting required.
education                      : object                         Formatting to LabelEncoding
education.num                  : int64                          No formatting required.
marital.status                 : object                         Formatting to LabelEncoding
occupation                     : object                         Formatting to LabelEncoding
relationship                   : object                         Formatting to LabelEncoding
race                           : object                         Formatting to LabelEncoding
sex                            : object                         Formatting to LabelEncoding
capital.gain                   : int64                          No formatting required.
capital.loss                   : int64                          No formatting required.
hours.per.week                 : int64                          No formatting required.
native.country                 : object                         Formatting to LabelEncoding
income                         : object                         Formatting to LabelEncoding

Step 2 - Bias and Weight Initialization¶

We will look at two (Normal and Uniform) where all other options can be found at: https://keras.io/api/layers/initializers/

Weight Initialization¶

  • Normal (Gaussian)
  • Uniform

Note, you can also add seed values to this function.

Convergence model from Hyperparameter Tutorial (default weight initializer - glorot uniform based)¶

In [3]:
# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 1
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed) # for TF this needs to be run per cell.


model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(1000, input_dim=14, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))


# Compile model
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer="adam", metrics=['acc'])

# Fit the model, but this time store the history (that is accuracy and loss for each Epoch)
results = model.fit(normalizedX, Y, validation_split=0.33, epochs=100, batch_size=1000, verbose=1, shuffle=True)


# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(results.history['loss'])
plt.plot(results.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

Train on 21815 samples, validate on 10746 samples

Normal Distribution Weight initializers¶

GlorotNormal

In [4]:
# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 1
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed) # for TF this needs to be run per cell.


model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(1000, input_dim=14, activation='relu', kernel_initializer="GlorotNormal"))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu', kernel_initializer="GlorotNormal"))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu' , kernel_initializer="GlorotNormal"))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu', kernel_initializer="GlorotNormal"))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))


# Compile model
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer="adam", metrics=['acc'])

# Fit the model, but this time store the history (that is accuracy and loss for each Epoch)
results = model.fit(normalizedX, Y, validation_split=0.33, epochs=100, batch_size=1000, verbose=1, shuffle=True)


# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(results.history['loss'])
plt.plot(results.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

Uniform Weight initializers¶

GlorotUniform

In [5]:
# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 1
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed) # for TF this needs to be run per cell.


model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(1000, input_dim=14, activation='relu', kernel_initializer="GlorotUniform"))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu', kernel_initializer="GlorotUniform"))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu' , kernel_initializer="GlorotUniform"))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu', kernel_initializer="GlorotUniform"))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))


# Compile model
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer="adam", metrics=['acc'])

# Fit the model, but this time store the history (that is accuracy and loss for each Epoch)
results = model.fit(normalizedX, Y, validation_split=0.33, epochs=100, batch_size=1000, verbose=1, shuffle=True)


# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(results.history['loss'])
plt.plot(results.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

Bias¶

We will compare the training time for the inclusion and exclusion of bias, noting that bias = True is the default value.

https://keras.io/api/layers/core_layers/dense/

The use of Bias¶

In [6]:
# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 1
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed) # for TF this needs to be run per cell.


model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(1000, input_dim=14, activation='relu', use_bias = True))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu', use_bias = True))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu', use_bias = True))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu' , use_bias = True))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))


# Compile model
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer="adam", metrics=['acc'])

# Fit the model, but this time store the history (that is accuracy and loss for each Epoch)
results = model.fit(normalizedX, Y, validation_split=0.33, epochs=100, batch_size=1000, verbose=1, shuffle=True)


# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(results.history['loss'])
plt.plot(results.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

No Bias¶

In [7]:
# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 1
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed) # for TF this needs to be run per cell.


model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(1000, input_dim=14, activation='relu', use_bias = False))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu', use_bias = False))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu', use_bias = False))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu' , use_bias = False))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))


# Compile model
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer="adam", metrics=['acc'])

# Fit the model, but this time store the history (that is accuracy and loss for each Epoch)
results = model.fit(normalizedX, Y, validation_split=0.33, epochs=100, batch_size=1000, verbose=1, shuffle=True)


# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(results.history['loss'])
plt.plot(results.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

Step 3 - Co-adaption¶

We will look at two techniques that will help regularize the network, that is to reduce the effects of co-adaption and over fitting.

Dropout¶

Added to both the input layer and hidden layers using defaul 20%

https://keras.io/api/layers/regularization_layers/dropout/

In [8]:
# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 1
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed) # for TF this needs to be run per cell.


model = Sequential()
model.add(Dropout(0.2, input_shape =(14,)))
model.add(Dense(1000, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))


# Compile model
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer="adam", metrics=['acc'])

# Fit the model, but this time store the history (that is accuracy and loss for each Epoch)
results = model.fit(normalizedX, Y, validation_split=0.33, epochs=100, batch_size=1000, verbose=1, shuffle=True)


# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(results.history['loss'])
plt.plot(results.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

Noise¶

Added to both the hidden layers using defaul 0.1 STD

https://keras.io/api/layers/regularization_layers/gaussian_noise/

In [9]:
# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 1
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed) # for TF this needs to be run per cell.


model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(1000, input_dim=14, activation='relu'))
model.add(GaussianNoise(0.1))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(GaussianNoise(0.1))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(GaussianNoise(0.1))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu'))
model.add(GaussianNoise(0.1))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))


# Compile model
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer="adam", metrics=['acc'])

# Fit the model, but this time store the history (that is accuracy and loss for each Epoch)
results = model.fit(normalizedX, Y, validation_split=0.33, epochs=100, batch_size=1000, verbose=1, shuffle=True)


# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(results.history['loss'])
plt.plot(results.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

Step 4 - Callbacks¶

Callbacks are useful tools during production training, and for significantly heaving Regularization techniques such as gridsearch. Also if the model fails during training, not all is lost if for example you save the weights. Early stopping can also be used to significantly speed up training and intensive gridsearches.

https://keras.io/api/callbacks/

Weight Saving (manually and using callbacks)¶

Manually saving the weights (these can be opened with any HDF5 reader).¶

Note we will be looking at saving the full model as a Tensorflow model in production.

In [10]:
# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 1
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed) # for TF this needs to be run per cell.


model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(1000, input_dim=14, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))


# Compile model
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer="adam", metrics=['acc'])

# Fit the model, but this time store the history (that is accuracy and loss for each Epoch)
results = model.fit(normalizedX, Y, validation_split=0.33, epochs=100, batch_size=1000, verbose=1, shuffle=True)


# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(results.history['loss'])
plt.plot(results.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()


# Saving the weights:
fileName = "myModel.HDF5"

model.save_weights(fileName)
print("Weights Saved as:", fileName)

# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 1
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed) # for TF this needs to be run per cell.


model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(1000, input_dim=14, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))


# Compile model
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer="adam", metrics=['acc'])


# Checkpointing
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint("myBest.hdf5", monitor='acc', save_best_only=True, mode="max", verbose=1)
callbacks_list = [checkpoint]


# Fit the model, but this time store the history (that is accuracy and loss for each Epoch)
results = model.fit(normalizedX, Y, validation_split=0.33, epochs=100, batch_size=1000, verbose=1, shuffle=True, callbacks=callbacks_list)


# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(results.history['loss'])
plt.plot(results.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

Early stopping¶

https://keras.io/api/callbacks/early_stopping/

patience: Number of epochs with no improvement after which training will be stopped.

In [12]:
# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 1
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed) # for TF this needs to be run per cell.


model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(1000, input_dim=14, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))


# Compile model
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer="adam", metrics=['acc'])


# Checkpointing
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint("myBest.hdf5", monitor='acc', save_best_only=True, mode="max", verbose=1)
earlystopping = EarlyStopping(monitor="val_loss",patience= 5)


callbacks_list = [checkpoint, earlystopping]


# Fit the model, but this time store the history (that is accuracy and loss for each Epoch)
results = model.fit(normalizedX, Y, validation_split=0.33, epochs=100, batch_size=1000, verbose=1, shuffle=True, callbacks=callbacks_list)


# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(results.history['loss'])
plt.plot(results.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

Step 5 - Grid Search¶

This is an exhaustive search, and also uses 3FCV to determine the best parameters for the final model. This will push the GPU for computational power, but if possible is a very strong method to regularise the model.

In [21]:
# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 1
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed) # for TF this needs to be run per cell.


def gs_model(optimizerIn='adam', initIn='GlorotUniform'):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(1000, input_dim=14, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=initIn))
    model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=initIn))
    model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=initIn))
    model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu' , kernel_initializer=initIn))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
     # Compile model
    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=optimizerIn, metrics=['acc'])
    return model


model = KerasClassifier(build_fn=gs_model)

# grid search epochs, batch size and optimizer
optimizers = ['rmsprop', 'adam']
inits = ['normal', 'uniform']
epochs = [100]
batches = [1000, 2000]


# Checkpointing
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint("myBest.hdf5", monitor='acc', save_best_only=True, mode="max", verbose=1)
earlystopping = EarlyStopping(monitor="loss",patience= 5)
callbacks_list = [checkpoint, earlystopping]


param_grid = dict(optimizerIn=optimizers, epochs=epochs, batch_size=batches, initIn=inits)

grid = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=param_grid)
grid_result = grid.fit(normalizedX, Y, callbacks=callbacks_list)

# summarize results
print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_))
means = grid_result.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = grid_result.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = grid_result.cv_results_['params']

for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    print("%f (%f) with: %r" % (mean, stdev, param))

In [16]:
# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 1
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed) # for TF this needs to be run per cell.


model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(1000, input_dim=14, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))


# Compile model
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer="adam", metrics=['acc'])


# Fit the model, but this time store the history (that is accuracy and loss for each Epoch)
results = model.fit(X_train_nor, Y_train_nor, validation_data=(X_test_nor,Y_test_nor), epochs=100, batch_size=1000, verbose=1, shuffle=True)


# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(results.history['loss'])
plt.plot(results.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

print("\n\nPerformance on normalized unseen data:")
print(model.evaluate(X_test_nor,Y_test_nor)[1] *100)


print("\n\nPerformance on raw un-normalized unseen data:")
print(model.evaluate(X_test_raw,Y_test_raw)[1] *100)

Adding class value as input attribute¶

We have used the train_test_split method to ensure that the splits are the same using the seed value.

In [18]:
# Convert to array
array = data.values

# get seperated input and classifies, using a deep copy of a list
XwithY = array[:,0:15]
Y = array[:,14]

scaler = preprocessing.Normalizer().fit(XwithY)
normalizedXwithY = scaler.transform(XwithY)



test_size = 0.33
# XwithY
X_train_withY, X_test_withY, Y_train_withY, Y_test_withY  = train_test_split(XwithY, Y, test_size=test_size, random_state=seed)

# normalized data
X_train_nor, X_test_nor, Y_train_nor, Y_test_nor  = train_test_split(normalizedX, Y, test_size=test_size, random_state=seed)



# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 1
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed) # for TF this needs to be run per cell.


model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(1000, input_dim=14, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))


# Compile model
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer="adam", metrics=['acc'])


# Fit the model, but this time store the history (that is accuracy and loss for each Epoch)
results = model.fit(X_train_nor, Y_train_nor, validation_data=(X_test_nor,Y_test_nor), epochs=100, batch_size=1000, verbose=0)


# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(results.history['loss'])
plt.plot(results.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()



print("\n\nPerformance on normalized unseen data:")
print(model.evaluate(X_test_nor,Y_test_nor)[1] *100)


print("\n\nPerformance with class as attribute:")
print(model2.evaluate(X_test_withY,Y_test_withY)[1] *100)
